ngs":["One of the many French names of Germanic origin that were introduced into Britain by the Normans; it has since remained in continuous use. It is derived from the nearly synonymous elements <i>hrōd</i> ‘fame’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’, and had a native Old English predecessor of similar form (<i>Hreodbeorht</i>), which was supplanted by the Norman name. Two dukes of Normandy in the 11th century bore the name: the father of  William the Conqueror  (sometimes identified with the legendary Robert the Devil), and his eldest son. It was borne also by three kings of Scotland, notably  Robert the Bruce  (  1274–1329 ), who freed Scotland from English domination. The altered short form <i>Bob</i> is very common, but <i>Hob</i> and <i>Dob</i>, which were common in the Middle Ages and gave rise to surnames, are extinct.  See also  Rupert ."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705190,"age":30,"year":"1290","julianDay":2192224,"title":"Jews Expelled From England","description":"After years of anti-Semitic behavior, King Edward I expelled Jews from England in 1290.","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"Sir Robert De Basing Alderman of London was born in 1260, in Little Easton, Essex, England as the son of Thomas de Basing. He married Margery de Basing in August 1290, in England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 2 sons and 1 daughter. In 1283, at the age of 23, his occupation is listed as sheriff. He died in 1303, in London, Middlesex, England, at the age of 43."},"et":{"1260–1303":"1260–1303","1258–1308":"1258–1308","–Male":"Surnud","1265–1316":"1265–1316","1277–1317":"1277–1317","1278–1316":"1278–1316","1295–1320":"1295–1320","1237–Male":"1237–Surnud","about 1277  eldest son":"umbes 1277","1295":"1295","1283":"1283","1260":"1260","1290":"1290","1316":"1316","1303":"1303","1237":"1237","1258":"1258","1278":"1278","1277":"1277","1320":"1320","1265":"1265","Est 1290":"august 1290","1308":"1308","1317":"1317","Kenardington, Ashford, Kent, Englan